<br>
Most fusion reations produce copious neutrons (just as a fission reactor does.)<br>
<br>
If a blanket of extremely common U238 is place in the fusion reactor, then Pu239 is produced.<br>
If common Thorium232 is used, then U233 is bred.<br>
<br>
These materials is easily extracted and can be used to build entire bomb stockpiles.<br>
<br>
The &quot;fusion/fission hybrid breeder&quot; is the near-term system of choice.<br>
&quot;Pure&quot; self-sustaining fusion reactors have not been built. But what has been designed CAN be used to breed fissiles and fuel fission reactors (or bombs)<br>
<br>
Possession of one of these makes a country a few fledged nucler weapons state.<br>
<br>
Even if in the future a pure fusion reator goes on the market, a proliferation nation or organization simply need to add the blanket and badda-bing, a-bombs.<br>
<br>
This is an unavoidable fact of physics<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Fusion reactors can be used as fission breeders...<br>
<br>
Any breeder is a large proliferation hazard and would have<br>
to be in a secure area with close government oversight....<br>
<br>
Even pure fusion has a significant proliferation hazard in that a rogue country or reactor operator could slip 238U in the blanket and breed plutonium. This potential proliferation hazard of a pure fusion reactor has received very little<br>
attention....<br>
<br>
Dr. Wallace Manheimer <br>
Senior Scientist for Fundamental Plasma Processes <br>
Naval Research Laboratory <br>
Washington DC<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
 However, because fusion neutrons could be used to generate fissile material, fusion power plants will have to be subject to international safeguards.<br>
--- United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> All these advanced nuclear energy systems will also unfortunately have potential use in the clandestine manufacture of weapon material. This is because nearly all systems envisioned so far either rely on a neutron flux to induce nuclear fission, or produce a neutron flux as a by-product of nuclear fusion. In all cases, safeguards will be required to verify that nuclear weapon materials are not being produced in the flux.<br>
--- William C. Sailor, Los Alamos Natl. Lab.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Pure fusion power, if developed as an economically attractive power source, would retain many of the technological connections with nuclear weapons, contributing to their substantial latent proliferation.<br>
